snippet.textDisplay:
HONESTY: To me Kobe was a villain because he was great and a Laker. I'm a die hard Heat fan. Me rooting against him on the court was a sign of respect to his greatness. In a weird way I actually became somewhat of a fan of Kobe's after the whole Colorado incident for several reasons (NOT PASSING JUDGEMENT ON WHAT HAPPENED BECAUSE I WAS NOT THERE). 

First: When he went back to Colorado to play the Nuggets, you could feel the tension through the television. People booed every chance they had. That type of reaction would not only distract many people but probably break them (i.e. Tiger Woods who was never the same after his incident). Kobe dropped 30+ on the Nuggets. I was impressed. Mental Fortitude. The beginning of Mamba Mentality.

Second: He was not a REPEAT OFFENDER. Before and after that incident you never heard anything obscene about the guy off the court. People make mistakes and there's those who made mistakes that humbled them (Michael Vick) WE all have done something we're not proud of or didn't get caught especially those of us who don't live our lives in the public eye. The only ones who continue to condemn someone after years of refinement are those who play Your Sin Is/Was Worst Than My Sin.

Third: His continuous support of the WNBA and female athletes

and Fourth: Being a father is the only thing it seemed Kobe enjoyed over being a Laker. I can respect that.
